Answer1.3:
Without more details or code about how you're 


  "extracting the current provider"


there's only so much to troubleshoot.

That being said, I would guess that your problem is a race condition between when Metamask is injecting web3 and when your code snippet above is being executed. 

MetaMask Injection ================== web3 inject! =====


Your Code          ======= exec * ======================
                   * const web3 = window.web3 
                   (but web3 not injected yet)


It might be helpful to consult the MetaMask FAQ Docs: 


  MetaMask injects web3 object and convenience Web3.js library into the javascript context. Look for this before using your fallback strategy (local node / hosted node + in-dapp id mgmt / read-only / fail)

  Note that the environmental web3 check is wrapped in a window.addEventListener('load', ...) handler. This approach avoids race conditions with web3 injection timing.


Most DApp detect and set web3 with a listener similar to something below.

window.addEventListener('load', function() {

  // Checking if Web3 has been injected by the browser (Mist/MetaMask)
  if (typeof web3 !== 'undefined') {
    // Use Mist/MetaMask's provider
    web3js = new Web3(web3.currentProvider);
  } else {
    console.log('No web3? You should consider trying MetaMask!')
    // fallback - use your fallback strategy (local node / hosted node + in-dapp id mgmt / fail)
    web3js = new Web3(new Web3.providers.HttpProvider("http://localhost:8545"));
  }

  // Now you can start your app & access web3 freely:
  startApp()
})


Alternatively, since you're using React, I'd recommend checking out the Truffle React Box which has a built in method for fetching web3 which prevents the race condition

